TQuestion.NOTES_DS:
This is an overall evaluation reflecting external exposures only and the exposures are determined by the hazards, combustible loading and distance to the exposure based on separation distances listed in Table 1-2 below.

“Protection” means adequate protection such as blank walls with proper fire rating, automatic exposure sprinklers, automatic fire shutters over glass windows or unprotected wall openings, wired glass, etc. in accordance to NFPA 80A.

  When other tenants are the exposure, use the “slight” or “negligible” rating if the client is well protected from the tenant. Rate moderate if protection is average and commensurate with the exposure (i.e. a store in a mall with standard 2-hr fire partition). Rate “severe” or “high” if tenant exposure is high or severe respectively.

Rating-Type of Exposure Rating Definitions

Negligible(10) -  >=100% of spatial separation requirements as defined in Table 4-2.

Slight(8) -  >=80% and <100 % of spatial separation requirements as defined in Table 4-2 or satisfactorily protected with passive barriers such as fire shutters, wired glass, blank masonry walls and fire doors protecting openings. Fire department accessibility is anticipated between the exposure and subject location.

Moderate(6) -  >= 70% and < 80% spatial separation requirements as defined in Table 4-2 or with active protection such as exposure sprinklers, possibly in combination with some passive protection. Fire department accessibility is anticipated between the exposure and subject location.

High(4) -  >= 60% and < 70% spatial separation requirements, but in no case less than 25 ft (7.6m). Passive barriers or active control systems are not in place. Early arrival of fire department could prevent a fire jump, but not always expected in every circumstance. Also, there may be some limitations relating to fire department accessibility at certain points between the exposure and subject location.

Severe(0) -  < 60% of spatial separation requirements or less than 25ft (7.6m). Significant fire department access limitations exist and a primary fire jump is anticipated. Equipment such as volatile chemical or flammable liquid tank farms, volatile chemical or flammable liquid rail tanker storage and significant yard storage which are in close proximity and expected to contribute significantly to fire communication.

This is an overall rating of the construction based on the predominate type of construction as listed in Table 5-1 except as explained in Note 2 below.

Rating-Type of Construction Rating Definitions

ISO 6 or Class AA (10)  -  Fire Resistive.

ISO 5 or Class A (8) -  Modified Fire Resistive.

ISO 4 or Class B (8) -  Masonry noncombustible with non-combustible metal deck roof.

ISO 3 or Class B (6) -  Non-combustible (Light non-combustible with non-combustible metal deck roof).
FM Approved Metal Sandwich Panels and EIFS (see note 3).
LPCB (Loss Prevention Certification Board) Approved Metal Sandwich Panels (see note 3).

ISO 2 or Class C (4) -  Joisted Masonry.
ISO 3/Class Band ISO 4/Class B with combustible metal deck roofs.

ISO 1 or Class D (0) -  Frame
Metal Sandwich Panels and EIFS (see note 3)

Water Supplies

Excellent (10)  - Two separate water supplies with each being capable of supplying 100% sprinkler demand, 100% hose/hydrant demand and 100% of the duration for the occupancy based on NFPA standards. *
OR
Two separate dedicated sprinkler system water supply meeting 100% of the demand for 100% of the duration requirements AND Two separate water supplies meeting 100% of the hose/hydrant demand and duration requirements. * *If pumps are needed on both supplies, (1) pump must be diesel or electric connected to a generator. Yard mains are looped with sectional control valves & have hydrants

Good (8)  - A single water supply capable of supplying 100% sprinkler demand, 100% hose/hydrant demand and 100% of the duration for the occupancy based on NFPA standards. *
OR
A dedicated sprinkler system water supply meeting 100% of the demand for 100% of the duration requirements AND A separate supply meeting 100% of the hose/hydrant demand and duration requirements. *
OR
When no sprinkler protection is required due to non combustible construction and no combustible loading and there are two separate water supplies meeting 100% of the hose/hydrant demand and duration requirements. *

Adequate (6) - A single water supply with a single pump capable of supplying at least 90% of the sprinkler demand, 100% hose/hydrant demand and 100% of the duration for occupancies based on NFPA standards.
OR
A dedicated sprinkler system water supply with a single pump meeting 90% of the demand for 100% of the duration requirements AND A separate supply meeting 100% of the hose/hydrant demand and duration requirements.
OR
When no sprinkler protection is required due to non combustible construction and no combustible loading and there is a single water supply meeting 100% of the hose/hydrant demand and duration requirements.

Nearly Adequate (4)  - A water supply capable of supplying at least 85% of the total water demand for sprinkler and hose/hydrant stream demand and 100% of the duration requirements based on NFPA standards.
OR
A water supply capable of supplying 100% sprinkler demand and 100% of the duration based on NFPA standards with no hose / hydrant available for manual fire fighting capabilities occupancy based on NFPA standardsA water supply capable of supplying at least 85% of the total water demand for sprinkler and hose/hydrant stream demand and 100% of the duration requirements based on NFPA standards.
OR
A water supply capable of supplying 100% sprinkler demand and 100% of the duration based on NFPA standards with no hose / hydrant available for manual fire fighting capabilities occupancy based on NFPA standards

Inadequate (0) - A water supply less than described above OR No water supply available at the plant site.
NB - Refer Serious Loss Exposure Guidance Ref 03-PM-03-0048

Supervision

AFD Automatic Fire Detection: (Note: For this section only, detection is considered to consists of smoke, heat, UVIR and automatic sprinklers).

Excellent(10) -  Detection is provided in 100% of the total area required and is monitored by a nationally recognized central station alarm monitoring company.

Good (8)  - Detection is provided in at least 90% of the total area required and is being monitored by one of the following methods:
A non nationally recognized central station alarm monitoring company.
An onsite and constantly attended proprietary monitoring station.
A remote but reliable proprietary monitoring station,
24/7 security making recorded rounds every 2-hours during idle times for all plant areas.

Adequate (6) - Detection is provided in at least 90% of the total area required with local alarms (which sound throughout the premises) and one of the following:
24/7 plant operations.
24/7 security making recorded rounds every 4-hours during idle times for all plant areas.

Inadequate (0) - Detection is less than indicated above.
Note 1: Total area required is defined as any area of combustible construction or occupancy.

Security:
Excellent(10) - Two security personnel on site 24/7 during idle times with one making recorded rounds every 2-hours.
AND
Full building and site intrusion alarms connected to a nationally recognized central station alarm monitoring company.

Good (8) - A security personnel member on site 24/7 during idle times making recorded rounds every 2-hours.
OR
Full building and site intrusion alarms connected to a non- nationally recognized central station alarm monitoring company.

Adequate (6) - A security personnel member on site 24/7 during idle times making recorded rounds every 4-hours.
OR
Intrusion alarms connected to a constantly attended location.

Nearly Adequate (4)  - Security personnel members on site 24/7 during idle times making non recorded rounds.
OR
Intrusion alarms not connected to a constantly attended location.

Inadequate (0) -  Security is less than indicated above.
NOTE: The above is for guidance only and the security at the site should be based on sound risk assessment taking into consideration the physical protections, systems, procedures and management commensurate with the risk and likely to prevent unauthorized persons from having access to the premises and/ or insured property in all normal circumstances, or to limit the available time to minimize theft loss.

meet the required demand and duration including the required hose/hydrant demands in accordance with NFPA or local equivalency.

Comments should be provided as necessary to justify selected scores.

Special Extinguishing Protection
Excellent(10) -  A fixed suppression system that is installed and inspected in accordance to NFPA requirements and is designed for at least two automatic and manual complete discharges.

Good (8) -  A fixed suppression system that is installed and inspected in accordance to NFPA requirements and is designed for a single automatic and manual discharge.

Adequate (6) -  Local fixed suppression systems are installed and inspected in accordance to NFPA requirements and is designed for manual discharge only.
OR
An automatic system designed to local codes / standards but does not conform to NFPA standards / requirements and is inspected / tested in accordance with NFPA.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Local fixed suppression systems are installed to NFPA requirements but is not inspected / tested per NFPA requirements.
OR
A manual system designed to local codes / standards but does not conform to NFPA standards / requirements and is inspected /tested in accordance with NFPA.

Inadequate (0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)NB - Refer Serious Loss Exposure Guidance Ref 03-PM-03-0048

NOTE: Where fixed protection/suppression is provided or warranted using NFPA criteria as the benchmark, then the engineer should apply an appropriate score of 10, 8, 6, 4 or 0 based on hazard scale, complexity and loss potential. Comments should be provided as necessary to justify selected scores.

Fire Extinguishing Agent (FEA)/Hose Reels
Excellent(10) -  Equipment is properly maintained and installed and fully accessible with no obstructions. For hose reels, the supply is from an adjoining overhead sprinkler system or a separate supply for other water protection systems in the area with a water supply adequate to exceed NFPA requirements. All inspections are completed exceeding NFPA minimum requirements and are properly documented with all records maintained and readily available. Plant personnel are formally trained in the correct usage of the equipment. There are no recommendations.

Good (8) -  Equipment is properly maintained and installed and fully accessible with no obstructions. For hose reels, the water supply is adequate to meet NFPA requirements. All inspections are completed in accordance with NFPA requirements and are properly documented with all records maintained and readily available. Plant personnel are formally trained in the correct usage of the equipment. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  Equipment is properly maintained and installed and fully accessible with no obstructions. For hose reels, the water supply is adequate to meet NFPA requirements. All inspections are completed in accordance with NFPA requirements and are properly documented with all records maintained and readily available. Plant personnel are formally trained in the correct usage of the equipment. Any recommendations are considered to be minor

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations or up to two “Advisory” recommendations.

Inadequate (0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)NB - Refer Serious Loss Exposure Guidance Ref 03-PM-03-0048

NOTE: Where fixed protection/suppression is provided or warranted using NFPA criteria as the benchmark, then the engineer should apply an appropriate score of 10, 8, 6, 4 or 0 based on hazard scale, complexity and loss potential. Comments should be provided as necessary to justify selected scores.

Public Fire Department

Excellent(10) -  Full time paid 24/7 FD within 5 miles (8km) and second Full time paid FD within 10 miles (16km), Fully trained and funded (adequate for the risk if special hazards exist), Fully equipped with required modern pumping appliances, ladders, aerial ladders, BA equipment equipment regularly tested and maintained, full time emergency communications centre to dispatch FD. Closest FD participates with other local full time paid FD’s within a “mutual aide” concept. A response time of 20 min or less is needed in addition.

Good (8) -  Full time paid 24/7 FD within 5 miles (8km), Fully trained and funded (adequate for the risk if special hazards exist), Fully equipped with required modern pumping appliances, ladders, aerial ladders, BA equipment equipment regularly tested and maintained, full time emergency communications centre to dispatch FD. Closest FD participates with other local full time paid FD’s within a “mutual aide” concept. A response time of 20 min or less is needed in addition.

Adequate (6) -  Volunteer FD with some full time/part time staff within 8 miles (13km), Fully trained and funded (adequate for the risk if special hazards exist), Fully equipped with required modern pumping appliances, ladders, aerial ladders, BA equipment equipment regularly tested and maintained, full time emergency communications centre to despatch FD. Closest FD participates with other local full time paid FD’s within a “mutual aide” concept. A response time of 20 min or less is needed in addition.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Part time, or retained/volunteer FD within 10 miles (16km), Capabilities are less than the above. There is enough water for manual hose streams if and when the volunteer/part time force arrives.

Inadequate (0) -  Less than indicated above or no public responders available.NB - Refer Serious Loss Exposure Guidance Ref 03-PM-03-0048
NOTE: Default to Adequate or Nearly Adequate at the most, when unsure and enough information isn’t known to confidently rate Good or Excellent.

Plan Emergency Organization and Planning

Excellent(10) -  When a Plant Emergency Organization includes a written Emergency Plan with precise instructions of emergency procedures, allocation of roles and responsibilities. Drills and practices are done periodically.Facility has an emergency organization that is commensurate with the exposure.

This ranges from evacuation to an interior structural fire suppression team or brigade.

Good (8) -  When a Plant Emergency Organization includes a written Emergency Plan with precise instructions of emergency procedures, allocation of roles and responsibilities Trainings and practices are done periodically but may need follow-up and updating of personnel for example.


Adequate(6) -  Facility has an emergency organization that is commensurate with the exposure. This primarily focuses on life safety, but does include fire service notification, de-energization of hazardous processes and energy supplies.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  When a Plant Emergency Organization has important weaknesses in a written Emergency Plan. Or it has not clearly defines the responsibilities or allocation of roles in it. Or it has failures in the communications and / or other aspects are not adequately covered.

Inadequate (0) -  No Plant Emergency Organization

Self-Inspection Program

Excellent(10) -  Regular, formal documented fire safety inspection being done. Interval of formal inspection is acceptable for the occupancy and associated hazards – minimum weekly. Checklist is used and items to be inspected are adequate for the occupancy and associated hazards. Inspectors are adequately trained for the inspection. Report will be reviewed and acted upon by senior management. Root cause of deficiency dealt with and resolved to prevent recurrence with changes to site working practice and procedures. Inspection records documented for future audit purposes. There are no recommendations.

Good (8) -  Regular, formal documented fire safety inspection being done. Interval of formal inspection is acceptable for the occupancy and associated hazards – minimum weekly. Checklist is used and items to be inspected are adequate for the occupancy and associated hazards with some minor additions. Inspectors trained but minor deficiencies noted. Report will be reviewed and acted upon by senior management.

Adequate (6) -  Inspection is carried out but one or two deficiencies are noted either not documented, informal or checklist inadequate or not used or frequency not adequate. Failing to meet the standards for ‘Good’

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations.

Inadequate (0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)

Impairment Procedures

Excellent(10) -  A written and documented impairment notification procedure, communicated to relevant personnel with designated management responsibilities assigned. The facility utilizes an automated computerized diary / log system to record all impairments and ensure restoration of protection as soon as practical. The practices utilize conforms to our impairment system which includes insurance carrier notification with proper documentation. There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  A written and documented impairment notification procedure, communicated to relevant personnel with designated management responsibilities assigned. The facility utilizes a paper manual system diary / log system to record all impairments and ensure restoration of protection as soon as practical. The practices utilize conforms to our impairment system which includes insurance carrier notification with proper documentation. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  A written and documented impairment notification procedure, communicated to relevant personnel with designated management responsibilities assigned. The practices utilized conform to our impairment system and all tags are maintained for review. There is no diary or logs utilized to record a master list. If there are no records, it can’t be “Adequate”. Any recommendations are considered to be minor

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations. The practice does not conform to our impairment system.

Inadequate(0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)

Contractor Management

Excellent(10) -  A written and computer documented training program which covers all aspects of plant safety and plant operations as it pertains to the site that covers all aspects as required by plant personnel. The training is required to be completed by all contractors and its sub contractor’s prior to being allowed onto the work on site. Contractor training records are maintained and easily accessible for review. The practice is strongly supported by plant management with a zero tolerance for misconduct or failure to meet the specified requirements. Requirements are to include all applicable management programs such as but limited to hot working, impairment handling, housekeeping and smoking policies. There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  Programs are as defined above with the exception that they are not computer based or records are not maintained electronically but are readily accessible. There are no recommendations.

Adequate (6) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in minor recommendations which are classified as “Advisory”

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations.

Inadequate (0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)

Hot Work Permit

Excellent(10) -  A written and documented hot work procedure, communicated to relevant personnel with designated management responsibilities assigned. The facility utilizes an automated computerized diary / log system to record and track all hot work activity and conducts fire and exceeds the requirements indentified in our hot work tag system. There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  A written and documented hot work procedure, communicated to relevant personnel with designated management responsibilities assigned. The facility utilizes a paper manual system diary / log system to record and track all hot work activity and conducts fire and conforms or utilizes our hot work tag system. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  A hot work permit program is in place and utilized. The practice utilized conforms to our hot work system and the only records are the collections of hot work tags that were completed and maintained for review. Any recommendations are considered to be minor or “Advisory”.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations or up to two “Advisory” recommendations. The practice does not conform to our impairment system.

Inadequate (0) -  Not conforming to the above or “Critical” recommendation(s)

Smoking

Excellent(10) -  No smoking allowed within the perimeter of the site, a strict no-smoking policy in place with disciplinary procedures for infringement. Regular weekly self-inspections undertaken by site to ensure rules observed. No issues observed during the site visit. There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  No smoking allowed within the premises other than designated external area only and rule fully observed. Regular weekly self-inspections undertaken by site to ensure rules observed. Appropriate receptacles are used and cigarette end is disposed of in appropriate manner daily. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  Smoking is restricted to designated and appropriate area only of the premises. Appropriate receptacles are used and cigarette end is disposed of in appropriate manner daily. Only minor risk improvement will be raised for minor infringement or tightening of controls.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations. The practice does not conform to our impairment system.

Inadequate (0) -  No formal smoking controls, rules or management enforcement in place resulting in uncontrolled smoking and poor disposal of smoking materials which will be subject to detailed risk improvement.

Housekeeping


Excellent(10) -  Housekeeping exceeds that which is commensurate for the occupancy. Regular self-inspection are conducted and documented by a safety or equivalent with management support. There are no recommendations There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  Housekeeping is commensurate for the occupancy and regular self-inspection are conducted and documented. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  Housekeeping is commensurate for the occupancy. Any recommendations are considered to be minor or “Advisory”.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations. The practice does not conform to our impairment system.
Inadequate (0) -  There are no formal housekeeping controls, rules or management enforcement in place. Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Critical” recommendations.

Planned Preventative Maintenance

Excellent(10) -  The preventative maintenance (PM) system is computer based and all import, key and critical components are captured in the system and inspection/ maintenance exceeds manufactures requirements / specifications for all critical components and meets the requirements for all remaining equipment. All maintenance work assignments are generated and tracked via the system. There is no overdue PM’s that exceeds 60 days. System should include all work that is required to be completed by outside contractors. There are no recommendations

Good (8) -  Conforms to the specifications as outlined above with the exception the system utilized is a non computer based system. There are no recommendations

Adequate (6) -  A PM practice in place capturing all key and critical components with inspection / maintenance conforming to manufactures minimum specifications. There are no overdue work assignments that exceed 90 day. Any recommendations are considered to be minor or “Advisory”.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies noted from above descriptions resulting in “Important” recommendations.

Inadequate (0) -  No formal programs in place and / or there are “Critical” type recommendations.

Management Interest

Excellent(10) -  Management takes a proactive approach and shows sincere interest in safety and risk management and is actively supportive of the survey process. They are involved in the communications and respond positively to comments / recommendations as they relate to improvements to current practices / procedures and actively encourage a culture of continuous improvement within their organization backed by formal audits and feedback. Based on review of the facility, it is evident that safety and risk management are a top priority to protect the business.

Good (8) -  Management shows sincere interest in safety and risk management and are actively involved in the survey process (e.g. attend opening/closing meeting, discuss recommendations, and provide information necessary to evaluate the risk). Based on review of the facility, it is evident that safety and risk management are a top priority.

Adequate (6) -  Management illustrates an interest in safety and risk management and is indirectly supportive by providing for the means when requested by plant staff after justification. They are only actively involved with the recommendations which require funding approval. All others are handled by plant personnel as part of their overall responsibilities. Based on review of the facility, it is evident that safety and risk management are important but not top priority by management.
Deficiencies result in “Advisory” recommendations.

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies result in “Important” recommendations

Inadequate (0) -  There is no or minimal management interest or there are deficiencies result in “Critical” recommendations

Site Level BCP
Excellent(10) -  There is a written and current business continuity plan in place which identifies and address how the facility would respond to all events that could lead to interruption of operations, business impact analysis for each one of them, and recovery strategies to limit the consequences of any incident.
 -   The plan is supported by and responsibility taken at senior management level within the organization with the document available as appropriate to all levels of operational management and subject to internal compliance and audit checking for the group and divisional level as appropriate. The crisis team is addressed in the plan (with functional roles & responsibilities assigned including deputies), and the plan is updated annually. Components of the plan are tested annually as part of the annually review process

Good (8) -  There is a written and current business continuity plan in place which identifies and address how the facility would respond to all events that could occur and that could lead to interruption of critical / key operations, business impact analysis for each of the critical or key components and recovery strategies to limit the consequences of any incident. The plan is supported by and responsibility taken at senior management level within the organization with the document available as appropriate to all levels of operational management and subject to internal compliance and audit checking for the group and divisional level as appropriate. The crisis team is addressed in the plan (with functional roles & responsibilities assigned including deputies), and the plan is updated annually. Components of the plan are tested annually as part of the annually review process

Adequate (6) -  There is a written and current business continuity plan in place which identifies and address how the facility would respond to common events that could occur and that could lead to interruption of critical / key operations, business impact analysis for each of the critical or key components and recovery strategies to limit the consequences of any incident. The plan is supported by and responsibility taken at plant management level with the document available as appropriate to all levels of plant operational management. The crisis team is addressed in the plan (with functional roles & responsibilities assigned including deputies), and the plan is updated annually. Deficiencies result in “Advisory” recommendations

Nearly Adequate (4) -  Deficiencies result in “Important” recommendations

Inadequate (0) -  There is no business continuity plan or there are deficiencies result in “Critical” recommendations
